AB  - This work represents a comparative uptake study of the toxic elements
arsenic, boron, 13 copper, manganese and zinc in monometallic and
multimetallic solutions by four green 14 microalgae species (
Chlamydomonas reinhardtii, Chlorella vulgaris , Scenedesmus 15
almeriensis and an indigenous Chlorophyceae spp . ), evaluating the
effect of pH and contact 16 time. Maximum removal efficiencies for
each toxic element were 99.4% for Mn ( C. 17 vulgaris , pH 7.0, 3h),
91.9% for Zn ( Chlorophyceae spp., pH 5.5, 3h), 88% for Cu 18 (
Chlorophyceae spp., pH 7.0, 10 min), 40.7% for As ( S. almeriensis, pH
9.5, 3h) and 19 38.6% for B ( S. almeriensis , pH 5.5, 10 min). B
removal efficiencies decreased remarkably in multimetallic solutions
(down to 0.2% in 21 C. reinhardtii ), except for Chlorophyceae spp .,
the only species isolated from a polluted 22 environment. FTIR spectra
shown the highest interactions for As (1150-1300 cm -1 ) and Cu 23
(3300, 1741, 1535, 1350-1400 cm -1 ). Results confirms microalgae
biomass as a potential 24 biosorbent for toxic elements. Chlorophyceae
was the most sensible specie, B and Cu interfering its growth. 28 
Except for C. vulgaris , lower toxic elements uptakes were found at pH
7. 29 The pH 5.5 enhanced Mn and Zn uptakes in Chlorophyceae sp, and
S. almeriensis.  Native Chlorophyceae sp., shown the best performance
in multimetallic studies. 31  FTIR spectra of C. reinhardtii shown
the different binding groups for each element.
